<concept id="c_transport">
    <title>Transport</title>
    <shortdesc/>
    <conbody>
        <p>Public transport is based on a fairly dense network of tram and bus routes operated by a
            municipal company, supplemented by a number of private minibus operators. Local trains
            connect some of the suburbs. The bulk of the city's historic area has been turned into a
                <xref href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pedestrian_zone" format="html"
                scope="external">pedestrian zone</xref> with rickshaws and horse-drawn carriages;
            however, the trams run within a three-block radius.<sup><xref
                    href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Krak%C3%B3w#cite_note-Krakow._Varied_Means_of_Transportation-153"
                    format="html" scope="external">[152]</xref></sup> The historic means of
            transportation in the city can be examined at the <xref
                href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Muzeum_In%C5%BCynierii_Miejskiej_w_Krakowie"
                format="html" scope="external">Museum of Municipal Engineering</xref> in the
            Kazimierz district, with many old trams, cars and buses.<sup><xref
                    href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Krak%C3%B3w#cite_note-154" format="html"
                    scope="external">[153]</xref></sup></p>
        <p>Railway connections are available to most <xref
                href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_cities_and_towns_in_Poland"
                format="html" scope="external">Polish cities</xref>, e.g. <xref
                href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Katowice" format="html" scope="external"
                >Katowice</xref>, <xref href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cz%C4%99stochowa"
                format="html" scope="external">Częstochowa</xref>, <xref
                href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Szczecin" format="html" scope="external"
                >Szczecin</xref>, <xref href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gdynia" format="html"
                scope="external">Gdynia</xref> and <xref href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Warsaw"
                format="html" scope="external">Warsaw</xref>. International destinations include
                <xref href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bratislava" format="html" scope="external"
                >Bratislava</xref>, <xref href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Budapest"
                format="html" scope="external">Budapest</xref>, <xref
                href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vienna" format="html" scope="external"
                >Vienna</xref>, <xref href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prague" format="html"
                scope="external">Prague</xref>, <xref href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Berlin"
                format="html" scope="external">Berlin</xref>, <xref
                href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hamburg" format="html" scope="external"
                >Hamburg</xref>, <xref href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lviv" format="html"
                scope="external">Lviv</xref>, <xref href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kyiv"
                format="html" scope="external">Kyiv</xref>, and <xref
                href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Odessa" format="html" scope="external"
                >Odessa</xref> (June–September).<sup><xref
                    href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Krak%C3%B3w#cite_note-International_railway_connections_from_Krak%C3%B3w-155"
                    format="html" scope="external">[154]</xref></sup> The <xref
                href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Krak%C3%B3w_G%C5%82%C3%B3wny_railway_station"
                format="html" scope="external">main railway station</xref> is located just outside
            the Old Town District and is well-served by public transport.</p>
        <p>Kraków's airport, officially named <xref
                href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Krak%C3%B3w_John_Paul_II_International_Airport"
                format="html" scope="external">Kraków John Paul II International Airport</xref>
                (<xref href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/IATA_airport_code" format="html"
                scope="external">IATA</xref>: <b>KRK</b>), is located 11 km (7 mi) west of the city.
            Direct trains cover the route between <xref
                href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Krak%C3%B3w_G%C5%82%C3%B3wny" format="html"
                scope="external">Kraków Główny train station</xref> and the airport in 20 minutes.
            Kraków Airport served around 5,800,000 passengers in 2017.<sup><xref
                    href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Krak%C3%B3w#cite_note-156" format="html"
                    scope="external">[155]</xref></sup> Also, the <xref
                href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Katowice_International_Airport" format="html"
                scope="external">Katowice International Airport</xref> is located 80 kilometres (50
            miles) or about 75 minutes from Kraków.<sup><xref
                    href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Krak%C3%B3w#cite_note-e-krakow-157"
                    format="html" scope="external">[156]</xref></sup></p>
        <p>In Autumn 2016 Poland's oldest <xref
                href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bicycle-sharing_system" format="html"
                scope="external">Bicycle-sharing system</xref> was modernized and now offers 1,500
            bikes at 150 stations under the name of Wavelo <i><xref
                    href="https://pl.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wavelo" format="html" scope="external"
                    >(pl)</xref></i>, which is owned by BikeU of the French multinational company
                    Egis.<sup><xref href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Krak%C3%B3w#cite_note-158"
                    format="html" scope="external">[157]</xref></sup></p>
    </conbody>
</concept>
